ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A modified polymerase chain reaction (PCR) technique in which bisulphite-converted methylated DNA target sequences are amplified in the presence of an excess of unmethylated counterpart sequences.

Concepts.definition: A modified polymerase chain reaction (PCR) technique in which bisulphite-converted methylated DNA target sequences are amplified in the presence of an excess of unmethylated counterpart sequences.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A visual acuity method using a pinhole occluder device, an opaque disk-shaped eye shield with one or more holes, that is used to differentiate between reduced visual acuity caused by refractive error and ocular pathology.

Concepts.definition: A visual acuity method using a pinhole occluder device, an opaque disk-shaped eye shield with one or more holes, that is used to differentiate between reduced visual acuity caused by refractive error and ocular pathology.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of flocculation method in which particles in suspension aggregate in loosely clumped microscopic masses, which are then detected via microscope.

Concepts.definition: A type of flocculation method in which particles in suspension aggregate in loosely clumped microscopic masses, which are then detected via microscope.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of flocculation method in which particles in suspension aggregate in loosely clumped macroscopic masses, which are then detected with the naked eye.

Concepts.definition: A type of flocculation method in which particles in suspension aggregate in loosely clumped macroscopic masses, which are then detected with the naked eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A method for estimating body surface area of second and third degree burns, based on assigned percentages for different regions of the body.

Concepts.definition: A method for estimating body surface area of second and third degree burns, based on assigned percentages for different regions of the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A method of assessing capillary fragility that is used in the diagnosis of hemorrhagic fevers. After taking a blood pressure measurement, the cuff is inflated to a point midway between the assessed systolic and diastolic pressures and maintained for five minutes; the cuff is then released and, after two minutes, the number of petechiae below the antecubital fossa are counted.

Concepts.definition: A method of assessing capillary fragility that is used in the diagnosis of hemorrhagic fevers. After taking a blood pressure measurement, the cuff is inflated to a point midway between the assessed systolic and diastolic pressures and maintained for five minutes; the cuff is then released and, after two minutes, the number of petechiae below the antecubital fossa are counted.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of a number of immunoassay-based techniques that use very small amounts (e.g., on a nanoliter scale) of biological fluids.

Concepts.definition: Any of a number of immunoassay-based techniques that use very small amounts (e.g., on a nanoliter scale) of biological fluids.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A technique to assess isometric muscle strength using a hand-held dynamometer.

Concepts.definition: A technique to assess isometric muscle strength using a hand-held dynamometer.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The measurement of the magnetic fields produced by electrical activity in the brain, usually conducted externally, using extremely sensitive devices. The measurement of electric fields in the brain provides information about the localization of brain activity which is complementary to that provided by electroencephalography.

Concepts.definition: The measurement of the magnetic fields produced by electrical activity in the brain, usually conducted externally, using extremely sensitive devices. The measurement of electric fields in the brain provides information about the localization of brain activity which is complementary to that provided by electroencephalography.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A psychometric response scale to assess subjective characteristics or symptoms, which relies upon a continuum of possible result values in between two fixed end-points.

Concepts.definition: A psychometric response scale to assess subjective characteristics or symptoms, which relies upon a continuum of possible result values in between two fixed end-points.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Use of restriction fragment polymorphism for detection of point mutations or other chromosomal changes.

Concepts.definition: Use of restriction fragment polymorphism for detection of point mutations or other chromosomal changes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A method to track an individual's physical activity using an activity monitor or other tracking device.

Concepts.definition: A method to track an individual's physical activity using an activity monitor or other tracking device.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An in vitro assay that is used to determine the presence of antibodies that are capable of eliciting effector cell-mediated lysis of target cells.

Concepts.definition: An in vitro assay that is used to determine the presence of antibodies that are capable of eliciting effector cell-mediated lysis of target cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay that uses a one-step process, where a labeled antibody binds the antigen of interest.

Concepts.definition: A type of enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay that uses a one-step process, where a labeled antibody binds the antigen of interest.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay that uses a two-step process, where a primary antibody binds the antigen of interest and then a labeled secondary antibody binds to the primary antibody.

Concepts.definition: A type of enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay that uses a two-step process, where a primary antibody binds the antigen of interest and then a labeled secondary antibody binds to the primary antibody.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An enzyme immunoassay technique that limits the amount of antigen available for binding in order to measure antibody avidity, with or without the use of a dissociation buffer.

Concepts.definition: An enzyme immunoassay technique that limits the amount of antigen available for binding in order to measure antibody avidity, with or without the use of a dissociation buffer.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An immunoassay method that involves the binding of antibodies to luciferase-labeled antigen, precipitation of the antibody/antigen complex, and analysis of the precipitate through the light-producing interaction of luciferase and luciferin.

Concepts.definition: An immunoassay method that involves the binding of antibodies to luciferase-labeled antigen, precipitation of the antibody/antigen complex, and analysis of the precipitate through the light-producing interaction of luciferase and luciferin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A flow cytometry technique that utilizes mass spectrometry to detect antibodies labeled with heavy metal ion tags that are bound to antigens of interest on single cells.

Concepts.definition: A flow cytometry technique that utilizes mass spectrometry to detect antibodies labeled with heavy metal ion tags that are bound to antigens of interest on single cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay that uses separate capture and detection antibodies that are bound to non-overlapping epitopes on the same antigen of interest.

Concepts.definition: A type of enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay that uses separate capture and detection antibodies that are bound to non-overlapping epitopes on the same antigen of interest.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An in vitro assay that is used to determine whether antibodies that can protect cells in culture from toxin activity are present in a biological specimen.

Concepts.definition: An in vitro assay that is used to determine whether antibodies that can protect cells in culture from toxin activity are present in a biological specimen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An invasive method that provides a direct measurement of fractional oxygen saturation in arterial blood by utilizing spectrophotometry.

Concepts.definition: An invasive method that provides a direct measurement of fractional oxygen saturation in arterial blood by utilizing spectrophotometry.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay that utilizes microfluidic channels to simultaneously measure analytes of interest.

Concepts.definition: A type of enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay that utilizes microfluidic channels to simultaneously measure analytes of interest.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A method for continuous recording of body movement that uses an actimetry sensor worn by an individual to measure rest/activity (sleep/wake) cycles. Monitoring can last several days to several weeks.

Concepts.definition: A method for continuous recording of body movement that uses an actimetry sensor worn by an individual to measure rest/activity (sleep/wake) cycles. Monitoring can last several days to several weeks.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The study of the mobility of the tympanic membrane and conduction bones through air pressure changes. It is used to detect middle ear abnormalities.

Concepts.definition: The study of the mobility of the tympanic membrane and conduction bones through air pressure changes. It is used to detect middle ear abnormalities.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of immunoassay in which a solution containing a target antigen is run through a membrane filter to which antibodies specific to the target antigen have been immobilized, and where antibodies labeled with colloidal gold nanoparticles are used for detection.

Concepts.definition: A type of immunoassay in which a solution containing a target antigen is run through a membrane filter to which antibodies specific to the target antigen have been immobilized, and where antibodies labeled with colloidal gold nanoparticles are used for detection.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of X-ray in which the images are not enhanced by the addition of contrast agents into the body.

Concepts.definition: A type of X-ray in which the images are not enhanced by the addition of contrast agents into the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of PET scan in which the images are not enhanced by the addition of contrast agents into the body.

Concepts.definition: A type of PET scan in which the images are not enhanced by the addition of contrast agents into the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A technique that measures an evoked potential caused by a visual stimulus and recorded by an electroencephalogram, used for those individuals who are unable to provide a verbal response to questions, including infants, toddlers, and other non verbal individuals.

Concepts.definition: A technique that measures an evoked potential caused by a visual stimulus and recorded by an electroencephalogram, used for those individuals who are unable to provide a verbal response to questions, including infants, toddlers, and other non verbal individuals.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A technique that assesses auditory function and/or type of hearing loss, in which a vibrating tuning fork (typically at 256Hz or 512Hz) is placed on top of the head or over the upper lip with the subject reporting whether sound is hear equally in both ears or whether the sound is louder in one ear.

Concepts.definition: A technique that assesses auditory function and/or type of hearing loss, in which a vibrating tuning fork (typically at 256Hz or 512Hz) is placed on top of the head or over the upper lip with the subject reporting whether sound is hear equally in both ears or whether the sound is louder in one ear.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A technique that assesses auditory function by comparing sound conduction through air versus the mastoid bone, in which a vibrating tuning fork (at 512Hz) is placed on the mastoid bone and the subject indicates when they can no longer hear the vibration, at which point the still vibrating tuning fork is moved 1-2cm from the auditory canal and the subject again indicates when they can no longer hear the fork.

Concepts.definition: A technique that assesses auditory function by comparing sound conduction through air versus the mastoid bone, in which a vibrating tuning fork (at 512Hz) is placed on the mastoid bone and the subject indicates when they can no longer hear the vibration, at which point the still vibrating tuning fork is moved 1-2cm from the auditory canal and the subject again indicates when they can no longer hear the fork.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An assay that is used to determine whether neutralizing antibodies that are present in a biological specimen can block viral infection/proliferation ex vivo, by counting the number of viral foci. This assay typically uses live virus.

Concepts.definition: An assay that is used to determine whether neutralizing antibodies that are present in a biological specimen can block viral infection/proliferation ex vivo, by counting the number of viral foci. This assay typically uses live virus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A diagrammatic method to test visual acuity that uses a set of cards with familiar pictures placed in either the top or bottom half of the card, used for those individuals who are unable to provide a verbal response to questions, including infants, toddlers, and other non verbal individuals.

Concepts.definition: A diagrammatic method to test visual acuity that uses a set of cards with familiar pictures placed in either the top or bottom half of the card, used for those individuals who are unable to provide a verbal response to questions, including infants, toddlers, and other non verbal individuals.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A method that enables simultaneous detection of multiple biomarkers on a single tissue section using immunohistochemistry techniques.

Concepts.definition: A method that enables simultaneous detection of multiple biomarkers on a single tissue section using immunohistochemistry techniques.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A method that enables simultaneous detection of multiple biomarkers on a single tissue section using immunofluorescence techniques.

Concepts.definition: A method that enables simultaneous detection of multiple biomarkers on a single tissue section using immunofluorescence techniques.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A procedure that uses sound waves to measure characteristics of disturbed bood flow, such as direction, velocity and turbulence. This enables the examiner to differentiate between normal and abnormal flow patterns and, in some cases, to quantitate those characteristics that are helpful in determining the severity of abnormal flow states.

Concepts.definition: A procedure that uses sound waves to measure characteristics of disturbed bood flow, such as direction, velocity and turbulence. This enables the examiner to differentiate between normal and abnormal flow patterns and, in some cases, to quantitate those characteristics that are helpful in determining the severity of abnormal flow states.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A screening assay for circulating complement proteins in which diluted serum samples are added to antibody-coated erythrocytes and the percentage of cell lysis is measured. The values are expressed in hemolytic complement units per milliliter (CH50), the dilution of serum required to lyse 50 percent of the erythrocytes in the assay.

Concepts.definition: A screening assay for circulating complement proteins in which diluted serum samples are added to antibody-coated erythrocytes and the percentage of cell lysis is measured. The values are expressed in hemolytic complement units per milliliter (CH50), the dilution of serum required to lyse 50 percent of the erythrocytes in the assay.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Optical coherence tomography used for imaging within blood vessels.

Concepts.definition: An optical coherence tomography imaging method that utilizes motion contrast imaging to capture the patterns of moving red blood cell reflectance across time and create high-resolution, 3D angiograms of vascular networks.
